\\n       - At 135ns: (a,b)=(0,0), state=1 -> q=1.\\n       - At 145ns: (a,b)=(0,0), state=1 -> q=0.\\n\\n2. **Construct the State Transition Table**:\\n   Let $S$ be the current state (state) and $I$ be the input (a, b).\\n   - If $S=0$:\\n     - (0,0) -> q=0 (at 15ns, 25ns...)\\n     - (0,1) -> q=1 (at 45ns)\\n     - (1,0) -> q=1 (at 55ns? No, at 55ns, a=1, b=0, state=1. Let\'s look at 55ns: a=1, b=0, state=1, q=0. This is a transition from state 1).\\n     - Let\'s re-examine carefully:\\n       - 15ns: state=0, q=0. Inputs at 10ns: (0,0).\\n       - 45ns: state=0, q=1. Inputs at 40ns: (0,0) - wait, the waveform says at 45ns, state is 0, q is 1. The inputs at 40ns were (0,0)? No, at 40ns a=0, b=0. At 45ns state is 0, q is 1. This means at 45ns, the input (0,1) at 45ns doesn\'t affect state yet. The state at 45ns is the result of inputs at 40ns.\\n       - Let\'s align: q at time T is the next state. state at time T is the current state.\\n       - Time 45: state=0, q=1. (Inputs at 40ns: a=0, b=0). So (a=0, b=0, state=0) -> next_state=1.\\n       - Time 55: state=1, q=0. (Inputs at 50ns: a=0, b=1). So (a=0, b=1, state=1) -> next_state=0.\\n       - Time 65: state=0, q=0. (Inputs at 60ns: a=1, b=0). So (a=1, b=0, state=0) -> next_state=0.\\n       - Time 75: state=0, q=1. (Inputs at 70ns: a=1, b=1). So (a=1, b=1, state=0) -> next_state=1.\\n       - Time 85: state=1, q=0. (Inputs at 80ns: a=0, b=0). So (a=0, b=0, state=1) -> next_state=0.\\n       - Time 95: state=0, q=1. (Inputs at 90ns: a=1, b=1). So (a=1, b=1, state=0) -> next_state=1.\\n       - Time 105: state=1, q=1. (Inputs at 100ns: a=1, b=1). So (a=1, b=1, state=1) -> next_state=1.\\n       - Time 115: state=1, q=0. (Inputs at 110ns: a=1, b=1). So (a=1, b=1, state=1) -> next_state=0? Wait, 105ns was state=1, q=1. 115ns is state=1, q=0. Inputs at 110ns: a=1, b=1. So (a=1, b=1, state=1) can be 0 or 1? Let\'s look closer.\\n\\n3. **Re-evaluating the waveform (Looking at inputs at the same time as the edge)**: